Date: Wed, 19 Jul 2000 00:42:20 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Business Wire; filed Tuesday, 18 Jul 2000 3:26 PM EST [edited

Increased Research Must be a Priority To Combat West Nile and Other
Vector-Borne Diseases
-------------------------------------------------------------------
"The detection of West Nile virus in _Aedes japonicus_ is worrisome because
this species of mosquito can bite humans and will do so during daylight
hours; this is different than the biting activity of _Culex_ mosquitoes,in
which the virus was found most frequently last year," stated Durland Fish,
Associate Professor in the Department of Epidemiology and Public Health at
the Yale School of Medicine.
Dr. Fish is the editor-in-chief of a new journal, Vector-Borne and Zoonotic
Diseases, to be published by Mary Ann Liebert, Inc., (www.liebertpub.com).
The finding of West Nile virus in a new mosquito vector, _ Aedes
japonicus_, demonstrates the adaptability of this exotic virus when it is
introduced into a totally new environment. While local governments have
spent at least $30 million on surveillance; none of this money is used for
research, which is essential in order to ensure the effectiveness of both
surveillance and control, Dr. Fish explained. "To my knowledge the National
Institutes of Health (NIH), have not allocated any funding for research in
the United States on the West Nile virus. Funding for research must be at
least commensurate with funding of surveillance efforts. The finding of
this new [vector species demonstrates the difficulties in understanding,
predicting, and ultimately preventing human risk of West Nile virus
infection. Research is the key to understanding the ecological processes
that control the virus in nature and that research must be
multi-disciplinary,"
