Date: Wed, 19 Jul 2000 00:37:23 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: AP Online, filed Tuesday, 18 Jul 2000 6:02 PM EDT [edited

NY Spraying To Kill West Nile virus
-----------------------------------
Health officials mobilized insecticide-spraying trucks Tuesday after an
encephalitis virus that killed seven people last year turned up again in
mosquitoes and birds across the New York City area. The spraying against
mosquitoes carrying the West Nile virus is being done only from trucks for
the time being. No plans for spraying from planes or helicopters have been
announced. State Health Commissioner Antonia Novello said Monday that the
virus had been found in mosquitoes collected in July in suburban
Westchester and Suffolk counties. Infected birds also have been found in
Westchester, Suffolk and Rockland counties and in New York City's Staten
Island.
Birds, like humans, get the virus from mosquitoes. No cases of the lethal
brain inflammation have been detected in people. But a human infection
"would be the next step we would expect to see," said Barbara Reynolds, a
spokeswoman for the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. In Suffolk
County on Long Island, health officials planned evening spraying Tuesday at
the Fire Island beach resort and in the towns of Lindenhurst and West
Babylon. The county was also distributing free bug repellent. New York
City officials planned to spray late Wednesday night and early Thursday in
sections of Staten Island. Spraying was also scheduled for Thursday evening
in 14 Westchester County communities, including Chappaqua, where the
President and Hillary Clinton have a home.
Elderly people or those with weakened immune systems are most at risk from
encephalitis. Last summer, in the first known appearance of the West Nile
virus in the Western Hemisphere, the disease killed seven people and
infected 62 others in the metropolitan area, prompting New York City to
undertake a huge aerial and ground spraying campaign.

[Byline: Verena Dobnik
