Date: Tue, 18 Jul 2000 16:53:05 -0400
From: Neville Clynes <ndc1@columbia.edu> [edited

The novelty of West Nile virus in the New York vicinity - a legitimate
question
I have not researched this question, but I am hoping someone can provide an
answer. What is the evidence that West Nile virus is in fact new to this
region? Have comparative serologic studies been done on saved serum? The
Queens area for example, where more of the cases came from, may have a
higher density of mosquitoes; for certain there are a lot more in Queens
than in Manhattan. I find it hard to believe that close to 4-5 % of the
population in the "epicenter" area were infected in a single year. So how
long has it been going on?
As an infectious disease physician in New York City I know that 10-15 cases
of encephalitis over a spring-summer-fall period could have been present
each year without anyone realizing the cause was West Nile virus. Lets face
it, a patient with encephalitis is usually treated empirically with
acyclovir and few if any tests are usually requested (with the exception
of a PCR for herpesvirus), especially in an elderly population. So I'm
sure I am missing the important data that assures us of a new phenomenon.
Otherwise we are in for never ending cycles in this the City and
surrounding States of insecticide sprayings.
[Susceptible birds, especially our migrating species, are unlikely to
visit only sprayed areas, and consequently at least a low level of endemic
West Nile virus [can be expected to persist in this region for the
immediate future. (And what about the past?)
--
Neville Clynes
Assoc. Professor of Clinical Medicine.
Columbia University
New York
<ndc1@columbia.edu>
[It is important to reiterate that there have been no human cases of
encephalitis attributable to West Nile virus infection so far this year.
The efficiency of transmission of West Nile virus to birds and humans by
_Aedes japonicus_ is an unknown quantity at present. Dr. Clynes adds a
relevant clinical perspective to the current situation. - Mod.CP
